Daily neck mobility routine you need to try!

When’s the last time you sat down to really stretch out your neck and shoulders?  Believe it or not most of our neck and shoulder tension can be prevented with just small amount of movement. Our spines were made to move, and nowadays, a lot of us sit in prolong positions that keep our spine still. These positions can cause a lot of pressure in our spine and joint and often times be the cause of our muscle aches and pains.

Give this daily neck routine a try the more you do it the more benefit you’ll get from it I recommend doing it once in the morning when you wake up and once at night before you go to bed it’s a great way to start your day and even better day to unwind and endthe night.

Perform 10 to 12 reps on each side 2 to 3 times daily .

Hip mobility! Why is it important? Let’s talk about…

As you age keeping your hips strong and healthy is so important for many movements such as standing, walking, bending etc. 

Mobility of the hips is important for anyone whether your an athlete, gym goer it doesn’t matter we all benefit from healthy hips. 

Our hips provide a stable base for our spine to keep our body upright, but also provide enough movement to allow our lower limbs to move around our spine. When we have poor hip mobility it can cause poor movement, poor posture habits and weak muscles which is often the cause of hip pain and discomfort. 

The saying “if you don’t use it, you lose it” is so true! 

In my office I see so many patients with hip pain some as young as 20 yo. It’s important to move your hips and if pain persists to see a chiropractor for an assessment. 

Hope you all take some time to move. Let me know how these feel!

Rounded shoulder fix🔥 You need to give these a try! Grab light weight dumbbell and let’s get to work! 

2 things are happening with rounded shoulder posture:

1️⃣Overactive muscles that have become tight and are pulling the shoulders into the forward position. The main culprits for this are often the pecs and the upper traps, in combination with a general lack of thoracic mobility.

2️⃣Underactive muscles that have become weak and are failing to pull the shoulders back into a neutral position. The main culprits for this are typically the traps (mid and lower) and the serratus anterior.

Do these exercises weekly to truly feel the benefits! 

Hope these help! 

Let me know if you struggle with rounded shoulders 👇🏼

Let’s talk 𝐜𝐚𝐫𝐩𝐚𝐥 𝐭𝐮𝐧𝐧𝐞𝐥! Do you struggle with arm/hand numbness, tingling or weakness? This one’s for you! Be sure to save this one.

𝑾𝒉𝒂𝒕 𝒊𝒔 𝒄𝒂𝒓𝒑𝒂𝒍 𝒕𝒖𝒏𝒏𝒆𝒍 𝒔𝒚𝒏𝒅𝒓𝒐𝒎𝒆? 
Carpal tunnel syndrome, also called median nerve compression, is a condition that causes numbness, tingling, or weakness in your hand. It happens because of pressure on the median nerve that passes through your carpal tunnel in your wrist.

𝑪𝒂𝒖𝒔𝒆𝒔? 
✔️Repetitive motions like typing or movements you do often with your wrists.
✔️Pregnancy 
✔️conditions like: hypothyroidism, rheumatoid arthritis, diabetes…

𝑬𝒙𝒆𝒓𝒄𝒊𝒔𝒆𝒔 𝒕𝒐 𝒕𝒓𝒚:
1️⃣prayers stretch 
2️⃣median nerve flossing 
3️⃣wrist flexor stretch

It’s important to see a chiropractor to  help you identify the cause!

Can I strengthen my core while pregnant? this is some thing I hear a lot from my pregnancy .The answer is absolutely with some variations. 

The dead bug exercise is a great core exercise to include while in your first trimester of pregnancy. This exercise works in a deep core muscle called the transverse abdominis which supports and stabilizes the spine and pelvis. 

As your belly expands, it may seem counterintuitive to work on strengthening the muscles around that area. After all, it increases in size as a natural part of pregnancy. It’s the most important muscle group of the abdomen, keeping your core muscles pliable and strong will decrease common pregnancy discomfort.

Let me know if you’d like me to share more pregnancy, safe core exercises with you.

It’s important to note that all exercises done during pregnancy should be approved by your doctor first .

Here’s why you might be experiencing back pain during pregnancy!! 

did you know that your upper back pain during pregnancy occurs when the weight of the baby and added body weight cause increased pressure on your muscles?

As baby grows your center of gravity shifts forward. This place is more pressure on your back muscles. Your body weight might also increase by 25 to 30% in a really short period of time and your back muscles may not be prepared to handle the extra strain. 

In preparation for delivery, the body releases, hormones that loosen ligaments and muscles, which produced stability specifically in the pelvis, and in our back and your back muscles need to work harder to maintain your posture and this is why I wanted to share my posture workout with you guys .

I started off with a band to warm up my back muscles and then proceeded with medium to lightweight for all of my exercises. I did this circuit three times and 10 to 12 reps each. 

Whether you’re pregnant or not, you can perform these exercises. Be sure to save this for your next workout !

Do you have a headache radiating from the base of your neck up to your head? You might have what’s called a cervicogenic headache!

Cervicogenic HAs are the result of tightness in the neck causing referred pain to the head and face.

Here’s exercises that can provide relief:

1.Suboccipital release: lay on your back place foam underneath the base of your skull sink in and enjoy release as long as you need.
2.Chin tucks/ resisted chin tucks: sit tall in neutral posture  and pull your chin into your neck making a double chin. Repeat 10-15 x to provide relief in upper neck 
3.Cervical traction: grab ends of towe/band and place it around base of your neck gently extend neck back while pulling up on. Repeat 5-6x.
4. Trapezius stretch: with one hand pull your ear to same shoulder and hold for 20-30secs repeat 2-3x each side 
5. Scapular squeezes: sit up nice and tall glue your elbows to your side, point thumb up and out and squeeze you shoulders blades together. Hold for 2-3 secs and repeat 10-15x.

Enjoy the relief!
